Calibration

Source: R/AllGenerics.R, R/fit.R
fit.Rd

Builds a calibration curve for gamma dose rate estimation.

fit(object, doses, noise, ...)

# S4 method for GammaSpectra,DoseRate,numeric
fit(object, doses, noise,
  range = c(200, 2800), intercept = TRUE, weights = FALSE,
  details = NULL, ...)

Arguments

object

An object of class GammaSpectra.
doses

A list of length-two numeric vectors giving the dose rate values and errors, respectively, for each element of object. Elements of the list will be matched by names to the references of the spectra.
noise

A list of two numeric values giving the noise value and error.
...

Currently not used.
range

A length-two numeric vector giving the energy range to integrate within (in keV).
intercept

A logical scalar: should the intercept of the curve be estimated?
weights

A logical scalar: should weights be used in the fitting process. If TRUE, the inverse of the squared dose errors are used.
details

A list of character vector specifying additional informations about the instrument for which the curve is built.

Value

An object of class CalibrationCurve.

See also

predict, integrateSignal

Examples

# Import CNF files for calibration
spc_dir <- system.file("extdata/crp2a/calibration", package = "gamma")
spc <- read(spc_dir, skip = TRUE)
## Select 'BRIQUE', 'C341', 'C347', 'GOU', 'LMP', 'MAZ' and 'PEP' to build the curve
spc_calib <- spc[c("BRIQUE", "C341", "C347", "GOU", "LMP", "MAZ", "PEP")]

# Set dose rate values and errors for each spectrum
known_doses <- list(
  reference = c("BRIQUE", "C341", "C347", "GOU", "LMP", "MAZ", "PEP"),
  dose_value = c(1986, 850, 1424, 1575, 642, 1141, 2538),
  dose_error = c(36, 21, 24, 17, 18, 12, 112)
)
## Coerce to a 'DoseRate' object
known_doses <- methods::as(known_doses, "DoseRate")

# Build the calibration curve
calib_curve <- fit(
  spc_calib,
  doses = known_doses,
  noise = c(value = 1190, error = 1),
  range = c(200, 2800)
)

# Check the linear model
summary(calib_curve[["model"]])

  ggplot2::labs(x = "Signal", y = "Dose rate [µGy/y]")
